{"id": "geo-ch8-sa01", "q_id": "geo-ch8-sa01", "topicId": "geo-ch8", "type": "short_answer", "subtopic": "Short/Long Answer", "question": "Define human resources. How do they differ from population?", "answer": "Human resources are people with knowledge, skills, health and abilities that contribute to development. Population refers only to the number of people. Population becomes human resources when it is educated, healthy and skilled.", "linksTo": "geo-rev-ch8-08", "linked_note_id": "geo-rev-ch8-08"},
{"id": "geo-ch8-sa02", "q_id": "geo-ch8-sa02", "topicId": "geo-ch8", "type": "short_answer", "subtopic": "Short/Long Answer", "question": "Differentiate between skilled and unskilled labour with examples.", "answer": "Skilled labour requires education or training and performs specialized tasks (doctor, electrician). Unskilled labour needs minimal training and relies on physical effort (manual loader, basic farm worker). Skilled workers are usually more productive and better paid.", "linksTo": "geo-rev-ch8-01", "linked_note_id": "geo-rev-ch8-01"},
{"id": "geo-ch8-sa03", "q_id": "geo-ch8-sa03", "topicId": "geo-ch8", "type": "short_answer", "subtopic": "Short/Long Answer", "question": "Explain why health is a key component of human resources.", "answer": "Health increases work capacity, reduces absenteeism and improves learning ability. Good nutrition, sanitation and health care raise productivity. Poor health raises dependency and reduces economic output, so health investment builds human capital.", "linksTo": "geo-rev-ch8-02", "linked_note_id": "geo-rev-ch8-02"},
{"id": "geo-ch8-sa04", "q_id": "geo-ch8-sa04", "topicId": "geo-ch8", "type": "short_answer", "subtopic": "Short/Long Answer", "question": "State the main physical and economic factors affecting population distribution in India.", "answer": "Physical factors: relief, climate, soil fertility and water availability. Economic factors: industries, transport networks, markets and urban services. These factors make plains and coasts dense while mountains and deserts remain sparse.", "linksTo": "geo-rev-ch8-03", "linked_note_id": "geo-rev-ch8-03"},
{"id": "geo-ch8-sa05", "q_id": "geo-ch8-sa05", "topicId": "geo-ch8", "type": "short_answer", "subtopic": "Short/Long Answer", "question": "What is occupational structure? Briefly describe the three sectors.", "answer": "Occupational structure shows how workers are distributed among primary, secondary and tertiary activities. Primary includes agriculture, fishing and mining; secondary includes manufacturing and construction; tertiary includes services like trade, transport, education and health.", "linksTo": "geo-rev-ch8-04", "linked_note_id": "geo-rev-ch8-04"}
